At this vast distance, we travel through space at 140 miles per second, rotating around the supermassive black hole at our Milky Way‚Äôs center. Nearer objects move faster. Stars closest to Sagittarius A* travel at 141,000 miles per second. The plasma surrounding the black hole‚Äôs event horizon orbits at 190,000 miles per second, superheats to a trillion degrees, then disappears. Within our galaxy, gravity wins, eventually, always.
